*Smarter Pricing Control Into Your Network*


Every network operates across two pricing planes =E2=80=94 one that defines=
 *what
you charge* and another that defines *what you pay*. Until now, these were
forced into a single pricing layer, making it harder to model margins,
manage costs, and scale confidently.

With this update, network owners and managers can now define *External* and
*Internal* pricing separately, giving you a clear, structured way to
control both sides of your network=E2=80=99s economics.
Why We Built This

As networks grow, pricing models become more sophisticated. A single
pricing structure could no longer represent both what is charged and what
is paid.

This created:

   -

   Limited flexibility in defining service rates
   -

   Compromised margin control
   -

   Tight coupling between pricing and payouts



By introducing  External and Internal pricing, the platform now mirrors how
modern logistic networks actually operate.
What=E2=80=99s New


Dual Pricing Configuration at the Network Level

Your network now supports *two pricing layers* - one for how services are
*charged*, and one for how services are *paid*.


This means delivery economics are no longer compressed into a single rule
set =E2=80=94 they run side by side, each with its own intent.


Every pricing screen now includes:

   -

   *External Price* =E2=80=94 where you define what you charge
   -

   *Internal Price* =E2=80=94 where you define what you pay

Both layers are powered by the *same pricing engine* you already use today.
So you get all the same flexibility, without needing to maintain two
different systems.

This separation is applied everywhere pricing exists:

   -

   *Base Pricing*
   -

   *Surge Pricing*
   -

   *And all other pricing-related sections*



So no matter what kind of rate you are setting, you always know whether it
governs what is *charged* or what is *paid* =E2=80=94 and can manage both w=
ith
clarity.


And because this structure is built into the platform, any new pricing type
introduced in the future will automatically support both sides of the
equation, keeping your financial model scalable and future-ready.
What This Means For You

You now get two independent pricing configurations in the network.

This means:

   -

   You can define what gets charged without impacting what gets paid
   -

   You can adjust margins, incentives, and costs independently
   -

   Your pricing logic becomes safer, clearer, and easier to evolve



Your network gains financial clarity without added operational complexity.
What=E2=80=99s Next


Something exciting is coming soon - a new way to set rates at participant
level.
Stay tuned !!
